        <p data-uuid="75f29c5f80fd4cc08d488c3baf9a90be">To form a political system for the region, Congress passed the <dfn title="Northwest Ordinance of 1787">Northwest Ordinance of 1787</dfn>.<b> </b>The ordinance established the <dfn title="Northwest Territory">Northwest Territory</dfn>,<b> </b>which included areas that are now in Illinois, Indiana, Michigan, Ohio, Minnesota, and Wisconsin. The Northwest Ordinance created a system for bringing new states into the Union. Congress agreed that the Northwest Territory would be divided into several smaller territories with a governor appointed by Congress. When the population of a territory reached 60,000, its settlers could draft their own constitution and ask to join the Union.</p>
        <p data-uuid="422ee1f7e0784b73b15485e6e730e919">In addition, the law protected civil liberties and required that public education be provided. Finally, the ordinance stated that “there shall be neither slavery nor involuntary servitude [forced labor] in the . . . territory.” This last condition banned slavery in the Territory and set the standard for future territories. However, slavery would continue to be a controversial issue.</p>
